vers the 1977 televised film The Gardener’s Son; McCarthy’s unpublished screenplays from the 1980s that became the foundation for his Border Trilogy novels and No Country for Old Men; various successful and unsuccessful productions of his two plays; and all seven film adaptations of his work, including John Hillcoat’s The Road (2009) and the Coen brothers’ Oscar-winning No Country for Old Men (2007). Emerging from this narrative is the central importance of tragedy—the rich and varied portrayals of violence and suffering and the human responses to them—in all of McCarthy’s work, but especially his writing for theater and film.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAuthors, Americany20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion picture authorshipxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion picture authorship--History and criticism. 0aMotion picture authorship. 0aPlaywritingxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aMcCarthy, Cormac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStage, Center, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31204940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477312056423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477312056/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK